quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The OR Operator[/h1]

The [b]OR [/b](||) operator returns true if any one of its operands is [b]true[/b]. [img id="2859" width="100%"] 
Example: [code format="cpp" codeId="215"]int age = 16;
int score = 90;
if (age > 20 [b]|| [/b]score > 50) {
    cout << "Accepted!" << endl;
}

// Outputs "Accepted!"[/code]
[note]You can combine any number of logical [b]OR [/b]statements you want.
In addition, multiple [b]OR [/b]and [b]AND [/b]statements may be chained together.[/note]

[h1]Logical NOT[/h1]

The logical [b]NOT [/b](!) operator works with just a single operand, reversing its logical state. Thus, if a condition is [b]true[/b], the NOT operator makes it [b]false[/b], and vice versa. [img id="2860" width="100%"] 
[code format="cpp" codeId="216"]int age = 10;
if [b]( !(age > 16) ) [/b]{
  cout << "Your age is less than 16" << endl;
}

// Outputs "Your age is less than 16"[/code]
